## Downstream Use Instructions

When this projection is used by AdversarialPlanReview:

- Treat this projection as the project-specific attack surface.
- Treat the plan being reviewed as suspect until it survives scrutiny.
- Use this projection to bias review toward this project’s unique failure modes.
- Attack plans that preserve wording while violating meaning.
- Attack plans that allow false milestone closure.
- Attack plans that blur authority across plan, milestone specs, operational context, code, or validation.
- Attack plans that defer decisions future execution agents should not make.
- Attack plans that duplicate capability ownership or acceptance authority.
- Attack plans that omit gates needed to protect invariants.
- Attack plans that hide dependencies or sequence validation too late.
- Use canonical vocabulary when describing findings.
- Do not let generic plan quality compensate for violating project-specific invariants.
- Do not modify this projection.

## Projection Integrity Checklist

Before finalizing, verify:

- The projection contains adversarial attack semantics only.
- No plan is reviewed.
- No findings are produced.
- No severity definitions are included.
- No patch format is included.
- No implementation guidance is included.
- Every retained statement helps an adversarial reviewer find project-specific plan failures.
- Every major retained statement traces to the Project Context or is clearly marked projection-local.
- Critical intent is explicit.
- Architectural invariants are explicit where available.
- Capability integrity rules are explicit.
- Authority boundaries are explicit.
- Dangerous dependency patterns are explicit.
- Planning invariants are explicit.
- False-success heuristics are explicit.
- Veto conditions are explicit.
- Canonical vocabulary is preserved.
- Generic review methodology has not been duplicated.
- The projection is compact enough to be passed into AdversarialPlanReview.
